Rifle was custom made in Kentucky and auctioned on Gunbroker last year. This rifle has been manufactured from the highest quality mil-spec parts available and is comparable and even superior in some ways to high quality rifles such as Colt, Daniel Defense and other high quality rifle manufacturers.

DO NOT buy an AR-15 or M4 Type Rifle Without Reading This ENTIRE Listing. 


Item Description 
SPECIFICATIONS: 
Model: Custom Built AR-15 M4 Style Rifle

Condition: New Unfired Pre-Lubed Ready to Fire

Lower Receiver Specifications

The lower receiver used in this build is a True MIL-SPEC forged lower, quality made using 7075 T6 aluminum (aircraft grade). The Lower was manufactured by DPMS. They make high quality MIL-SPEC lowers. Before you buy an AR-15 always make sure that the lower receiver is a Forged Lower Receiver made with 7075 T6 aluminum. 	   
Lower Parts Kit Specifications 

The lower parts kit used in this build was made by a military contractor CMMG. These are true mil-spec lower parts used by the military and other large manufacturers. These are high quality lower parts made to last. Before you buy an AR-15 always make sure that the lower parts kit is from a reputable manufacturer and are not made from polymer parts. Some manufacturers use cheap imported parts from overseas that will not last long under the high heat and pressure of firing multiple rounds quickly. Always ask about each part before buying an rifle. If the seller cannot or will not tell you where the parts come from beware. 	   
Buffer Tube & Buffer/Action Spring Specifications 

The 6 position adjustable UTG stock allows you to fit the rifle to your needs and has been built to meet all military specifications. What does this mean for you? First and foremost, you get the best possible fit between the stock body and the tube, cancelling any rattle that might occur with cheaper stocks. Oh, and did we mention the tube is 100% made in the USA? We have pulled out all the stops to create and craft the best Mil-Spec AR stock on the market. The only place to start is with the UTG Mil-Spec T6 Stock. The buffer tube used in this build is mil-spec and was made with 7075 T6 aluminum (aircraft grade). These are true mil-spec buffer tubes made with military grade materials and mil-spec diameter. The tube also includes a carbine action spring and carbine buffer. Before you buy an AR-15 you should ask for the specifics of the buffer tube. Many sellers will call their buffer tube "mil-spec" simply because the diameter of the tube is mil-spec, but you should also ask what type of aluminum it was made from. If it was not made from 7075 T6 it will not be as durable and could possibly bend on you under heavy stress. Don't settle for mil-spec diameter, insist on mil spec materials as well. 	   
Buttstock Specifications 

The 6 position adjustable stock allows you to fit the rifle to your needs and has been built to meet all military specifications. What does this mean for you? First and foremost, you get the best possible fit between the stock body and the tube.	   
Pistol Grip Specifications 

The Pistol Grip used in this build is a mil-spec Magpul MOE Plus Pistol Grip. The MOE+ Grip combines reinforced polymer body construction with comfortable, wrap-around rubber overmolding for maximum weapon control in adverse environments. With a similar shape to a 'medium' sized MIAD, this AR15/M16 drop-in design features a hard-polymer bottom edge to reduce the possibility of equipment snags or grip damage. The MOE+ Grip accepts optional storage cores for gear stowage and includes a basic grip cap. This is the most comfortable pistol grip that Magpul makes. Don't settle for a cheap plastic pistol grip, make sure it's a Magpul.




Upper Receiver Specifications 

The Upper Receiver used in this build is a Forged, Mil-spec Stag Arms A3 flat top upper Manufactured using 7075 T6 aircraft-grade aluminum with M4 feed ramp cuts and Hard Anodized in Dark Black. It includes a mil-spec Forward Assist Assembly, Ejection Cover Door Assembly, and a Billet Aluminum Heavy Duty Charging Handle. Before you buy an AR-15 always make sure that the upper receiver is a Forged and made with 7075 T6 aluminum. 	   
Bolt Carrier Group Specifications 

The Bolt Carrier Group used in this build is Nickel Boron Coated from WMD Guns. The bolt carrier group is one of the most important parts of any rifle. The Nickel Boron Coated Bolt Carrier Group from WMD Guns is one of the absolute best bolt carrier groups available period! 

The bolt is Carpenter 158 case hardened steel that has been shot peened and magnetic particle inspected. It is Manufactured to Government drawings with Mil-Spec gas rings and NiB-X coated (40% more wear resistant than Chrome).

The Extractor is manufactured, heat treated, and hardened per Government drawings. It also includes a black extractor buffer and heavy duty spring and is also NiB-X coated.

The Firing Pin is manufactured, heat treated, hardened, Chromed and certified per Government drawings.

The Carrier is an M16 style full auto carrier (heavy weight), 8620 material, heat treated and case hardened. The Manufacturing tolerances on inside diameters is tightly controlled. NiB-X coated for durability and ease of cleaning.

The Gas Key is Hardened to USGI Specifications and attached using grade 8 hardened fasteners. Permatex No. 3D Aviation Form a gasket Type III Sealing Compound per MIL-S-45180 used on assembly. NiB-X coated. Staked per military specifications.

The Cam pin is Manufactured, heat treated, hardened and certified per Government drawings. NiB-X Coated.

Before you buy an AR-15 you must ask the following questions about the Bolt Carrier Group: 
Who is the manufacturer of the bolt carrier group? 
Is the bolt made from 158 Carpenter Steel? 
Is the bolt shot peened? 
Is it Magnetic Particle Inspected? 
Is it Nickel Boron Coated for durability?
If any of the answers are No then you have a very inferior unreliable bolt carrier group. Many sellers skimp on this part and buy cheap off brand bolt carrier groups. This is one part that you should never cut corners on! Make them tell you who manufactures the bolt carrier group and what it's specs are.

WMD Guns Nib-X BCG Review

The Gas Tube used in this build is a Carbine Length Mil-Spec Gas Tube. 	   
Gas Block Specifications 

The Gas Block used in this build is a Yankee Hill Machine Low Profile Gas Block. This gas block provides a simple, low profile design that can be used to mount a mid-length forearm to a carbine length barrel. Manufactured from high quality steel and finished with a mil. spec. phosphate coating. This gas block has a bore diameter of .750 inches. 	   
Free Float Quad Rail Specifications 

The Free Float Quad Rail used in this build is very high quality with “T” marked rails to mark accessory locations. It utilizes anti-rotation screws for secure installation. The forearms and barrel nuts are made of 6061-T6 aluminum and hardcoated to military specifications. The jam nut and anti-rotation screws are steel and plated a matte black finish to match.

Always ask what type of rail is installed before buying an rifle. Free float rails are much better than 2 piece rails because they allow for greater accuracy. Since Free Float rails do not put any strain on the barrel it allows the rifle to be much more accurate. Try to stay away from 2 piece rails that bolt directly to the barrel because the extra weight and pressure on the barrel will decrease the accuracy of your rifle. Always go free float if you can. 	   
Vertical Grip Specifications 

The Front Vertical Grip used in this build is a Bipod Grip. Designed for use with 1913 Picatinny railed hand guards, the Bipod Grip is similar to the famous Grippod. It is quickly removable with no tools and provides a stationary platform for shooters to use. 	   
Flash Hider/Compensator Specifications 

The Compensator/Flash Hider used in this build is an aggressive tooth Phantom Comp/Flash Hider. title: For Sale:  Walther P38 - P1 9m/m Luger Cal. Semi-Auto Pistol
location: South East Virginnia, Virginia, United States

NOTE: it is the buyers responsibility to confirm that this firearm is legal to own in your state and/or locality.

Offered for your consideration is one (1) Walther P38 – P1 semi-automatic pistol chambered in the very popular 9m/m, (9X19m/m – Luger), caliber. This P1 is in excellent condition showing only very minor finish wear on a few sharp edges. It comes with a period German camouflaged holster, cleaning kit, original Walther P1 magazine, and owners manual. It was manufactured in April, 1974.

In late 1963 the postwar military model P1 was adopted for use by the German military, identifiable by the P1 stamping on the slide. The postwar pistols, whether marked as P38 or P1, have an aluminum frame rather than the steel frame of the original design. The aluminum frame was later reinforced with a hex bolt above the trigger guard. During the 1990s the German military started replacing the P1 with the P8 pistol and finally phased out the P1 in 2004.

Additional pictures upon request.

•Action: Semi-auto.

•Extras: Period German camouflaged holster, cleaning kit, original Walther P1 magazine, and owners manual.

•Blemishes: Very minor finish wear on a few sharp edges.

title: For Sale:  Tommy Gun .45 ACP Rifle, Thompson Copy, Made in USA
location: Bellingham - Mt. Vernon, Washington, United States
postcontent:
I have here for sale a  Volunteer Enterprises Commando.  These were built in the 60's and 70's in  Knoxville, Tennessee.  It shoots standard .45 ACP ammo in semi-auto fashion from a closed bolt using a simple blow-back action and very few moving parts.   Has a real operational muzzle brake, 16" barrel and beautiful walnut furniture.  The rear stock, butt plate and sling loop are original Thompson (that's just what Volunteer Enterprises used).  The bluing is 80-90% in my opinion, and overall the gun looks very nice.  It's very fun to shoot, but mostly it's fun to just hold and look at!  It is very iconic. I've only fired a couple of magazines through it, but for me it functioned flawlessly, with no failures.  It is pretty quiet with almost no recoil, but makes a big hole!  My young son can handle it easily.   It uses standard grease gun stick mags, and a high-capacity one is included.  
This is a fairly inexpensive reproduction of the Thompson, but that being said this gun DOES NOT feel "cheap".  I have owned a couple of the GSG .22 cal copies (like the HK and AK47), and this Thompson does NOT feel like them.  It's heavy; probably about the same weight of an original Thompson, and just feel dense, heavy and solid in your hands.  The Walnut furniture is generous in proportions and great feeling in your hands.  It is impossible to not draw people over when at the range.  It's just cool.

The only trades I might be interested in would be for a magnum revolver made by Colt or S&W only.  I could add $ to the deal for the right gun.  For cash, the price is firm.  I would like to see a CWP or other "good guy" card to complete the sale.   If it's listed, I still have it.  To weed out scammers, e-mails without contact phone numbers will be ignored.


Thanks for looking, and have a great day!
